  "prompt": "How does someone become a Canadian diplomat?",
  "response": "To become a Canadian diplomat, one typically follows these steps:\n\n1. Education\n- Bachelor's degree (preferably in international relations, political science, economics, or a related field)\n- Some candidates pursue a Master's degree in international studies or public policy\n\n2. Language Requirements\n- Fluency in English and French is strongly preferred\n- Bilingualism is highly valued in the Canadian diplomatic service\n\n3. Apply to Global Affairs Canada\n- Complete the Foreign Service Officer (FSO) selection process\n- Pass a rigorous written exam\n- Undergo multiple interview stages\n- Complete extensive background checks\n\n4. Competitive Selection\n- Limited number of positions available annually\n- Candidates must demonstrate:\n- Strong analytical skills\n- Cross-cultural communication abilities\n- Adaptability\n- Strategic thinking\n- Leadership potential\n\n5. Training\n- Successful candidates complete the Foreign Service Officer Training Program\n- Learn diplomatic protocols, international relations, and specific job skills\n\n6. Career Progression\n- Start in entry-level diplomatic roles\n- Potential postings in Canadian embassies and consulates worldwide\n- Opportunities for advancement based on performance\n\nAdditional suggestions include gaining international experience, developing language skills, and networking within diplomatic circles.",
